The document starts at a high level data exploratory faces and delves deeper into analyis and concludes with a suggested route to market based on the analyis.

The command below contains the funciton used to address the NA in the data mentioned in question 3.

completeFun <- function(data, desiredCols) {
  completeVec <- complete.cases(data[, desiredCols])
  return(data[completeVec, ])
}

bbibu <- completeFun(bb, "IBU")
bbabv <- completeFun(bb, "ABV")
bba <- completeFun(bbabv,"IBU")

*The code below results in mean, max, min, median, sd by state for IBU and ABV and merges the two stat dataframes into one:

bbmibu <- summaryBy(IBU ~ State, data = bba, 
          FUN = list(mean, max, min, median, sd))
bbmabv <- summaryBy(ABV ~ State, data = bba, 
          FUN = list(mean, max, min, median, sd))
bbstat <- merge(bbmabv,bbmibu,by="State")

One of the more complex questions asked out of the analysis was to investigate the difference with respect to IBU and ABV between IPAs (India Pale Ales) and other types of Ale. Using KNN which a statistical model used to classify like items together I created model that tested ABV and IBU as predictors to whether or not a beer was and IPA or a regular Ale.

What you see below are the statistical results of that model. You can see that accuracy that the IBU and ABV can be used a predictors of IPA vs Ale is at 87% which is at a minimum shows high correlation. Looking further into the statistics it shows that it easier to determine whether a beer isnt an IPA using ABV and IBU more than it is good a predicting if it is.

bbibu$IPA <- ifelse(grepl("IPA", bbibu$Style), "yes", "no")
bbibu$Ale <- ifelse(grepl("Ale", bbibu$Style), "yes", "no")


bbibu1 <-subset(bbibu, (IPA =='yes')  || (Ale =='yes'))



trainIndices = sample(1:dim(bbibu1)[1],round(.20 * dim(bbibu1)[1]))
train = bbibu1[trainIndices,]
test = bbibu1[-trainIndices,]

classifications = knn(train[,c("ABV","IBU")],test[,c("ABV","IBU")],train$IPA, prob = TRUE, k = 6)
table = table(classifications,test$IPA)
confusionMatrix(table)

Since the executive staff showed interest in the relationship IBU and ABV as it pertained to determining whether a beer was an IPA or an Ale I extended the analysis to view ABV distibution for IPAs and theyre Styles to determine potential areas of market entry into the IPA space.

Looking at the historgram below in comparison to the histogram of abv for all beers its easy to see that is more common for IPAs to have a higher ABV:

bbuIPA <- subset(bbibu, (IPA =='yes'))

ggplot(bbuIPA, aes(x= ABV)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Another interesting finding with IPAs there is a stronger correlation between bitterness and alcohol content seen in the scatter plot below:

ggplot(data = bbuIPA, mapping = aes(x = ABV, y = IBU)) +
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Finally looking at the histogram from earlier with an overlay containting beer style it is easy to see the the Imperial IPA dominates the high alcohol content IPA space:

bbuIPA <- subset(bbibu, (IPA =='yes'))

ggplot(bbuIPA, aes(x= ABV, fill = IBU , color = Style)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

With a bit of research into the IRI: US Beer Sales data set it was shown that the more popular IPAs did not have the level of bitterness or percieved hopppiness of the average Imperial IPA. With this information I believe that there is a strong case into looking int creating a high abv IPA with a lower IBU to compete in a untapped market space.
